SIMPLE: revert
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revert
<hw>Re*vert"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Reverted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Reverting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>revertere</ets>,
<ets>reversum</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>vertere</ets> to
turn: cf. OF. <ets>revertir</ets>. See <er>Verse</er>, and cf.
<er>Reverse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn back, or to the
contrary; to reverse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till happy chance <qex>revert</qex> the cruel scence.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tumbling stream . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Reverted</qex>, plays in undulating flow.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To throw back; to reflect; to reverberate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To change back. See
<er>Revert</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To revert a series</b></col> <fld>(Alg.)</fld>, <cd>to
treat a series, as <mathex>y = a + bx + cx<exp>2</exp> + etc.</mathex>,
where one variable <it>y</it> is expressed in powers of a second
variable <it>x</it>, so as to find therefrom the second variable
<it>x</it>, expressed in a series arranged in powers of
<it>y</it>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Revert
<hw>Re*vert"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To return; to come
back.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So that my arrows⟦br⟧
Would have <qex>reverted</qex> to my bow again.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To return to the proprietor after
the termination of a particular estate granted by him.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To return, wholly or in part,
towards some preexistent form; to take on the traits or characters of an
ancestral type.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To change back, as from a soluble
to an insoluble state or the reverse; <as>thus, phosphoric acid in
certain fertilizers <ex>reverts</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revert</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Revert
<hw>Re*vert"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who, or that which,
reverts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An active promoter in making the East Saxons converts, or rather
<qex>reverts</qex>, to the faith.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reverted</ent>⟦br⟧
